<paragraph blockId="24.[132,1237,1090,1378]" pageId="24">
The two smaller larvae identified below appeared in most respects identical to that of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Plebeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latitarsis" subGenus="Scaura">
<emphasis box="[1217,1237,1091,1116]" italics="true" pageId="24">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[142,222,1128,1154]" italics="true" pageId="24">Scaura</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[241,342,1128,1154]" italics="true" pageId="24">latitarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
including the same estimated length of 
<quantity box="[824,919,1128,1155]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.8" pageId="24" unit="mm" value="5.8">5.8 mm</quantity>
. However, the mandibular apex of 
<taxonomicName box="[229,401,1165,1191]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Plebeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coccidophila">
<emphasis box="[229,401,1165,1191]" italics="true" pageId="24">P. coccidophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is substantial shorter and more robust contrasting with the elongate slender tapering mandibular apex of 
<emphasis box="[580,717,1202,1228]" italics="true" pageId="24">
<taxonomicName box="[580,712,1202,1228]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Plebeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latitarsis">P. latitarsis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
